But this is how it starts, and this is a crazy way to start.

03:24.703 --> 03:35.757
It says this, Luke 2, 1, in those days a decree went out from Caesar Augustus that the whole empire should be registered.

03:36.378 --> 03:39.442
This first registration took place while Quirinius

03:39.874 --> 03:44.759
was governing Syria, so everyone went to be registered each to his own town.

03:45.901 --> 04:02.579
Now this might be one of those sections that we just tend to skip over when we think about the Christmas story and reading about Jesus, like who cares about Caesar, Augustus, I don't even know who this coroniest guy, I don't even know how to say his name.

04:03.460 --> 04:05.042
You know, who cares?

04:05.346 --> 04:10.853
But so we tend to like to skip to the part where Jesus is born.

04:12.135 --> 04:16.140
But this is a very important place to start.

04:16.200 --> 04:20.926
This really sets up the Christmas story, the story of Jesus.

04:22.308 --> 04:27.314
You see, this is the part that is relatable.

04:29.154 --> 04:58.770
that the mentioning of these rulers of Caesar Augustus, of the census being decreed, it's a painful reminder to all those who are in Israel that they're still in captivity, that they're still under the rule of the Romans, and that they're land, the land that God promised them all those years ago, isn't really their land, it's Rome's.

04:59.906 --> 05:07.736
In this census, isn't just some kind of self-voluntary census like the people knocking on your doors today, right?

05:08.737 --> 05:09.919
It's not just to count people.

05:09.939 --> 05:22.254
Most likely this census was used to see how much money, how many taxes, that the Roman government can squeeze out of the people that are living in Israel.

05:22.294 --> 05:28.402
So nobody, not even back then, like taxes, especially those in Israel.

05:28.898 --> 05:39.012
So I think the, but I think the author of Luke is very intentional with starting off this story of Jesus' birth this way.

05:39.913 --> 05:46.282
Because he seems to set it up in a way that is realistic to the world that they're living in.

05:46.322 --> 05:57.618
You see, I can only imagine that Jews during this time, under the persecution of these different foreign leaders, were just looking at their world like,

05:57.698 --> 06:02.484
Man, this world is crazy and Romans did some crazy stuff.

06:04.626 --> 06:20.405
But you see, we're lucky today because we can look back on this story and those who are familiar with this story already know that this savior of the universe, Jesus, was being born.

06:21.827 --> 06:27.634
And we know that all the craziness in the world wouldn't matter because Jesus was now present

06:27.906 --> 06:38.103
on earth, and we know that he would perform miracles, he would heal people, he would deliver them, he would set them free, all those who believed in him.

06:38.143 --> 06:42.791
But if you were a first century Jew, you wouldn't have known that yet.

06:43.953 --> 06:51.346
You would have been waiting hundreds of years for the long-awaited Messiah that they always talked about.

06:52.898 --> 06:57.766
And this is why this verse that happens later on, I think is very important.

06:57.806 --> 07:02.333
Luke 2, 10, it says, but the angels said to them, don't be afraid.

07:02.794 --> 07:11.869
For look, I proclaim the good news of great joy that will be for all the people today in the city of David as Savior was born for you.

07:11.949 --> 07:14.834
Who is the Messiah, the Lord?

07:15.746 --> 07:36.434
Now just to give a brief overview, like I said, if you weren't able to catch the full flow of scriptures that were read today, just to give a little recap of where we're at, the census brought Joseph and Mary to Bethlehem because that's where Joseph had to check in and do his due diligence.

07:36.546 --> 07:37.367
for the census.

07:37.828 --> 07:47.239
Now mind you, Mary was pregnant at the time with Jesus and they had traveled all the way from their hometown of Nazareth to Bethlehem.

07:48.020 --> 07:55.088
Now I had the privilege of visiting Israel earlier this year and Nazareth is not close to Bethlehem at all.

07:56.270 --> 08:03.659
So this would have been about a three to four day journey and unfortunately there was no Ubers available.

08:03.679 --> 08:06.482
So it would have been on a donkey or on foot.

08:07.682 --> 08:15.494
And of course, you know, the time that Mary, for Mary to give birth happens to be while they're on this trip to Bethlehem, right?

08:15.554 --> 08:16.475
Always perfect timing.

08:17.637 --> 08:24.327
And so they end up having to find a place for Mary to give birth.

08:25.308 --> 08:28.093
And ultimately they end up finding that place.

08:28.513 --> 08:29.435
Everything works out.

08:30.356 --> 08:32.860
She ends up giving birth to Jesus.

08:33.240 --> 08:37.106
Again, not in the most ideal of conditions, but it happens.

08:38.466 --> 08:42.790
But then this story transitions in such a weird way.

08:42.850 --> 08:51.899
If you really, sometimes we read it so much we don't really catch this, but the story transitions in a really random way.

08:52.119 --> 08:56.383
You see, if I was writing this story, I would just end it right there.

08:58.225 --> 09:03.590
Like that seems like a logical place to stop the climax of the story.

09:03.690 --> 09:06.893
Jesus, the savior of the world is born.

09:07.013 --> 09:08.274
Boom, and a story.

09:08.450 --> 09:10.153
go on to Him when He's older.

09:11.716 --> 09:14.381
But that isn't how the story ends.

09:16.184 --> 09:18.769
It doesn't end on Jesus being born.

09:18.829 --> 09:30.149
And I think that's really intentional because instead it jumps to some random shepherds who are in the same region that Mary and Joseph are in.

09:30.209 --> 09:32.754
And these shepherds aren't even given a name.

09:33.762 --> 09:38.268
All that's mentioned about them is that they were just working in the field throughout the night.

09:39.849 --> 09:44.175
And while they were there, an angel of the Lord appeared to them.

09:45.797 --> 09:50.002
And he told them, hey, I got some good news for you.

09:50.082 --> 09:52.125
And this is the verse we just read, verse 10.

09:53.046 --> 09:54.948
The angel of the Lord said, don't be afraid.

09:55.008 --> 10:00.875
I proclaim to you good news of great joy.

10:00.915 --> 10:03.058
That will be for all the people.

10:06.018 --> 10:08.461
And then he adds this at the end.

10:09.142 --> 10:10.924
He said, today your Savior will be born to you.

10:12.045 --> 10:14.528
Who is the Messiah, the Lord?

10:15.769 --> 10:17.331
Now let's stop here for a second.

10:18.993 --> 10:21.756
You know, what is the Messiah?

10:21.856 --> 10:22.777
What does this mean?

10:22.857 --> 10:24.279
Why is this significant?

10:24.299 --> 10:26.101
Why is this important?

10:26.241 --> 10:27.643
And we're through this series.

10:27.703 --> 10:33.810
If you've been tagging along, we've been talking through different titles of Jesus.

10:35.298 --> 10:39.685
Well, Messiah is a word that we really don't use in our culture, and I haven't seen it.

10:40.486 --> 10:45.975
We don't use it much in our culture today, so it's understandable if most people don't know what it means.

10:47.177 --> 10:49.761
It comes from the Hebrew word, mashiach.

10:50.523 --> 11:02.482
And because the New Testament was written in Greek, they translated this word to Christos instead of Messiah, which we translate today as Christ.

11:03.426 --> 11:09.535
And this is why some versions of this Bible, if you have a different version, says Christ the Lord in this section instead.

11:10.737 --> 11:16.625
But contrary to popular belief, Christ is not actually Jesus' last name.

11:17.767 --> 11:18.908
I know, mind blown.

11:18.928 --> 11:20.290
Some of you guys are like, what?

11:21.472 --> 11:23.054
My whole life is a lie.

11:23.074 --> 11:26.880
So Christ is not actually Jesus' last name.

11:26.980 --> 11:31.026
It's just a title for Jesus.

11:31.874 --> 11:39.264
And because Messiah in Christ have the same meaning which they both mean anointed one.

11:40.787 --> 11:44.512
Now as you can see from the graphic.

11:46.114 --> 11:57.330
Now you see Messiah was a title that carried a lot of way Jews in this day would know exactly what this title implied.

11:58.242 --> 12:12.719
Because anyone who was anointed, and they would anoint them with oil in the Old Testament, was someone who was deemed chosen by God to fulfill a specific purpose.

12:12.739 --> 12:13.921
So this was a big deal.

12:15.142 --> 12:21.970
The person who was anointed would act as a bridge, a connection point between God and his people.

12:22.882 --> 12:32.495
which is why this title is normally just given this anointing procedure was only given to priests, kings, and prophets.

12:34.017 --> 12:47.474
So for an angel of the Lord to come and tell these shepherds in this field that the Messiah, the anointed one, was born not just among them, but for them, that was huge.

12:48.962 --> 12:59.857
Now what I find fascinating about this part of the story is that it really paints a picture of who Jesus is and who he came to save.

12:59.897 --> 13:03.301
You see, Jesus is the anointed one.

13:03.381 --> 13:11.692
He will find later that he is the king, that he is the high priest, and that he is the prophet all in one.

13:11.753 --> 13:15.858
And he came to save everybody.

13:17.890 --> 13:36.954
You see this greeting that the angels came with this, I proclaim to you, good news, this was a greeting that was given often by the Romans, usually as a way to proclaim the birth of an heir to the emperor, or the coming of age, or their ascension to the throne.

13:37.614 --> 13:43.762
And because of this, usually when the Romans did this, this message was given to everybody,

13:44.962 --> 13:47.665
Usually it was in a very over the top way, right?

13:47.705 --> 13:48.526
Celebration.

13:48.586 --> 13:59.578
And this was so that everyone knew and understood that the person being born was important.

14:00.019 --> 14:13.394
Whenever this message came, and yet here in this story, we see an angel of the Lord giving this message of good news to a group of unnamed shepherds

14:13.826 --> 14:19.511
in the middle of the night, in an insignificant region of Bethlehem.

14:22.534 --> 14:30.542
And just to give you a little more picture of what this is, shepherds were despised by most religious people.

14:32.143 --> 14:33.625
Because they were the grunt workers.

14:33.685 --> 14:35.547
They did what nobody else wanted to do.

14:35.587 --> 14:43.314
They usually slept alongside the animals that they were taken care of out in the fields.

14:44.802 --> 14:49.630
And this shepherding job was set aside for people who were low in status.

14:49.671 --> 14:52.676
And that's why it's usually was kids that are shepherds.

14:54.439 --> 14:59.868
It was by no means a job that anybody of any importance had.

15:01.431 --> 15:09.906
But here the first people that are notified about the King of Kings birth are shepherds.

15:12.162 --> 15:19.710
And like I said, I believe this is a clear glimpse into the purpose and mission of Jesus' life.

15:20.111 --> 15:30.983
It was a glimpse of showing how Jesus was the one true savior, the true Messiah, the anointed one that the whole world needed.

15:31.023 --> 15:41.554
And I love how this story ends, the angel tells the shepherds that they could find this savior, rap tightly,

15:41.826 --> 15:47.475
lying in a manger, and once the angels left, the shepherds actually want to go search for Jesus, and they found them.

15:48.577 --> 15:56.709
They told Mary and Joseph of what happened, you know, what they seen, and when they were leaving, it says this.

15:58.452 --> 16:09.970
It says, the shepherds return glorifying and praising God for all the things they had seen and heard, which were just as they had been told.

16:11.106 --> 16:19.157
One of the commentaries I read pointed out that this contrast between the Caesar Augustus and Jesus.

16:21.821 --> 16:30.112
You see, Augustus, he had this decree forcibly made people follow this decree.

16:31.153 --> 16:32.956
He lived richly in a palace.

16:32.976 --> 16:37.522
They would only be born, these kings would only be born in important cities.

16:39.490 --> 16:42.854
And his authority and prominence was all by force.

16:44.156 --> 16:56.372
And yet here, Jesus, the anointed one, was born in this unknown city, lying in a manger with animals around.

16:56.412 --> 17:03.742
